To solve this problem we will break it down into three parts as requested:

## Step 1: Part (a)
The condition for Čerenkov radiation to be produced is that the speed of the charge must exceed the phase velocity of light in the material. The refractive index n of the material can be related to its phase velocity v_p via:
\[ v_{p}=\frac{c}{n}\]
where c is the vacuum speed of light.
For a relativistic particle moving at speed βc, where β=v/c, the frequency ω' observed from the point of view of the source is given by Doppler shift formula,
\begin{align*}
    f'(f)&=f(1-\beta cos(\theta))
\end{align*}

However, since the observer sees the signal delayed due to the fact that the front edge of the pulse travels slower than the back edge, there's also a time delay factor involved when calculating the apparent frequency seen by the stationary observer. This results in the following expression for the observed frequency f'' :
\begin{align*}
   f''&=(1+\beta cos(\theta))f\\
   &=nf
\end{align*}
Since the wavelength λ' observed is inversely proportional to the frequency f', then 
\begin{align*}
     \lambda'= \frac{\lambda'}{(1 - \beta \cos (\theta))}
\end{align*}
But because the observed frequency f'' is equal to nf, so the observed wavelength should be
\begin{align*}
      \lambda'' & = \frac{n\lambda }{(1- \beta \cos (\theta ))}
\end{align*}
Now using Snell’s law, we know that sin θ_n = n * sinθ_o , here θ_n is the critical angle, or the angle beyond which total internal reflection occurs, while θ_o is the incident angle. In our case, however, we have no incidence on any surface but rather a straight trajectory of the particle inside the medium. Therefore, we consider only the relation between the angles without considering the concept of incidence and refraction together. We want to find out how fast does the particle travel compared to the speed of light within the medium. So let us use the equation above directly relating the two speeds:
\begin{align*}
       \sin \theta &= \sqrt {1-(\frac{1}{n})^{2}} \\
        \therefore \qquad \cos \theta &= \pm \sqrt {\frac{1-n^{2}}{n^{2}}} \\  
         \text{and }\qquad \beta &= \frac{v}{c}\\
          \Rightarrow \qquad \beta &= \frac{1}{n} \left[1+ \left(n^{2}-1\right)^{\frac12}\right]   
\end{align*}

## Step 2: Part (b)

We now calculate the minimum kinetic energy required for an electron to produce Čerenkov radiation in the specified conditions. To do this, note that if the electron emits Čerenkov radiation, then its speed must satisfy the inequality derived earlier:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:inequality}
\frac{1}{n} \left[1+ \left(n^{2}-1\right)^{\frac12}\right]> \frac{v}{c}.
\end{equation}
In other words, the right-hand side represents the threshold below which Čerenkov radiation cannot occur. Now solving the equality instead gives us the threshold value of beta, i.e.,
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{n} \left[1+ \left(n^{2}-1\right)^{\frac12}\right]&= \frac{v}{c}\\
\implies \qquad \gamma &= \frac{1}{n} \left[1+ \left(n^{2}-1\right)^{\frac12}\right]\\
\end{align*}
Using the definition of gamma ($\gamma = \frac{E}{mc^2}$), we get
\begin{align*}
 E-mc^2&= \frac{1}{n} \left[1+ \left(n^{2}-1\right)^{\frac12}\right]\cdot mc^2\\
\implies \qquad E&= \frac{1}{n} \left[1+ \left(n^{2}-1\right)^{\frac12}\right]\cdot mc^2+m c^2\\
\end{align*}
Plugging in values for n,m,c, and converting units appropriately yields the result:
\begin{align*}
E&= \frac{1}{1.00135}(1+(1.00067)\cdot .5)+.500\\
&=.5017+.4998\\
&=1.0015MeV
\end{align*}

## Step 3: Part (c)
Given that the momentum p of the incoming particle is much larger than its rest mass m₀, we may write the four-vector kμ as follows:
kμ=[ω,p], where ω=p²/m₀-c²≈pc⁄m₀. Then the four-acceleration aμ is simply d/dt(kμ)=d/dt([ω,p])=[dp/dt,0].
From special relativity, dp/dt=F=m₀a, hence [dp/dt,0]=[F,0]=e[E+v×B,0]=(ev,B). Thus, the rate of change of the photon number N per unit volume V is
\begin{align*}
\frac{dN}{dt}&=-\int_V \omega \frac{d\rho}{dt} dV\\
&=-\int_V \omega e B_z dv\\
&=-\frac{eB_z}{V} \int_V \omega dV\\
&=-\frac{eB_z}{V} \langle \omega \rangle V\\
&=-eB_z \langle \omega \rangle
\end{align*}
Here ρ denotes the electric field strength, and 〈⋅〉 indicates averaging over space. Note that ∫∂ρ/∂tdV=d(dρ)/dtV=d(N/V)/dt=dne/dt, where ne is the free-electron density. Also, ω=e(E+v×B)·k/e=E·k, where · denotes dot product. Using the dispersion relation nk=c, we obtain
\begin{align*}
\frac{dk_x}{dx}&=\frac{k_y}{x}=nk_y/n=n\frac{|k|}{nx}=\frac{n}{nx}|k|=|\mathbf{k}|/\rho\\
\end{align*}
Thus, the intensity I of the Čerenkov radiation is given by
I=Nℏω=−eBz⟨ω⟩=−eBzℏ|k|/ρ
Note that |k|=√((π/neλ)²+k⊥²)=(π/neλ)|k⊥|. Here, λ is the wavelength of the Čerenkov radiation, and k⊥ is the component perpendicular to the direction of motion. Hence,
\begin{align*}
I&=-eB_z ℏ \frac{|k_\perp|}{\rho}\\
&=-eB_z ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda \rho} \frac{|k_\perp|}{|k|}
\end{align*}
As mentioned before, the angle between the directions of motion and observation is denoted by θ. From geometry, we see that |k||k⊥|=|k|^2sin(θ).
Therefore,
\begin{align*}
I&=-eB_z ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda \rho} \frac{|k|^2 \sin \theta}{|k|}\\
&=-eB_z ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda \rho} |k| \sin \theta\\
&=-eB_z ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda \rho} \frac{nc}{\lambda} \sin \theta\\
&=-eB_z nc ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda^2 \rho} \sin \theta
\end{align*}
Recall that the power P transmitted through area S is defined as P=SIE, where I is the intensity. If we assume that all photons generated are detected, then the ratio of the measured flux F to the actual flux J is just the solid-angle fraction ΔΩ/S, where ΔΩ is the solid angle subtended by the detector aperture. That is,
\begin{align*}
\frac{F}{J}&=\frac{\Delta \Omega}{S}\\
\end{align*}
Hence, the uncertainty δP in the measured power is
\begin{align*}
\delta P&=\frac{\partial P}{\partial x_i} \delta x_i\\
&=\frac{\partial(P)}{\partial \theta} \delta \theta\\
&=(-eB_z nc ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda^2 \rho} \cos \theta)(\delta \theta)\\
&=-eB_z nc ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda^2 \rho} \cos \theta \delta \theta
\end{align*}
Similarly, the uncertainty δJ in the true power is
\begin{align*}
\delta J&=\frac{\partial J}{\partial x_i} \delta x_i\\
&=\frac{\partial(J)}{\partial \theta} \delta \theta\\
&=(-eB_z nc ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda^2 \rho} \cos \theta)(\delta \theta)\\
&=-eB_z nc ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda^2 \rho} \cos \theta \delta \theta
\end{align*}
Dividing these expressions, we finally arrive at the desired fractional error:
$$\frac{\delta P}{P}=\frac{-eB_z nc ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda^2 \rho} \cos \theta \delta \theta}{(-eB_z nc ℏ \frac{\pi}{\lambda^2 \rho} \cos \theta )}=\delta \theta.$$
Substituting numerical values, we get
$\frac{\delta m_0}{m_0}=\delta \theta=10^{-3}$


